

Beck Hansen, known by his stage name Beck, is an American singer, songwriter, rapper, record producer, and multi-instrumentalist. He is known for creating musical styles that draw from a wide range of genres, including hip hop, alternative rock, folk, and country. He has released thirteen studio albums, two of which, Odelay (1996) and Sea Change (2002), received critical acclaim. He has won multiple awards, including four Grammy Awards, and has been nominated for twelve others.

Beck was born in Los Angeles in 1970 to a mother of Canadian and English descent and a father of Swedish and Norwegian descent. He began his musical career as a teenager, playing in a local garage band. He moved to New York City in 1989 and began to perform at small clubs and coffeehouses. He released his first single, "Loser," in 1993, which quickly gained popularity and was widely played on alternative radio stations. His first album, Mellow Gold, was released in 1994 and featured the single "Loser," which peaked at number 10 on the Billboard Hot 100.

Beck's second album, Odelay, released in 1996, was a critical and commercial success. It featured the singles "Where It's At," "Devils Haircut," and "The New Pollution," all of which charted on the Billboard Hot 100. The album was nominated for Album of the Year at the 1997 Grammy Awards and won two awards, including Best Alternative Music Album.

Beck's third album, Midnite Vultures (1999), was also a critical and commercial success. It featured the singles "Sexx Laws," "Mixed Bizness," and "Debra," all of which charted on the Billboard Hot 100. The album was nominated for Album of the Year at the 2000 Grammy Awards and won two awards, including Best Alternative Music Album.

Beck's fourth album, Sea Change (2002), was a departure from his previous albums. It featured a more somber, introspective sound and was critically acclaimed. The album featured the singles "Lost Cause" and "The Golden Age," both of which charted on the Billboard Hot 100. The album was nominated for Album of the Year at the 2003 Grammy Awards and won two awards, including Best Alternative Music Album.

Beck's fifth album, Guero (2005), was a return to his more upbeat sound. It featured the singles "E-Pro," "Girl," and "Hell Yes," all of which charted on the Billboard Hot 100. The album was nominated for Album of the Year at the 2006 Grammy Awards and won two awards, including Best Alternative Music Album.

Beck's sixth album, Modern Guilt (2008), was a return to his more introspective sound. It featured the singles "Chemtrails" and "Gamma Ray," both of which charted on the Billboard Hot 100. The album was nominated for Album of the Year at the 2009 Grammy Awards and won two awards, including Best Alternative Music Album.

Beck's seventh album, Morning Phase (2014), was a return to his more somber, introspective sound. It featured the singles "Blue Moon" and "Waking Light," both of which charted on the Billboard Hot 100. The album was nominated for Album of the Year at the 2015 Grammy Awards and won three awards, including Album of the Year and Best Alternative Music Album.

Beck's eighth album, Colors (2017), was a return to his more upbeat sound. It featured the singles "Up All Night," "Dear Life," and "Dreams," all of which charted on the Billboard Hot 100. The album was nominated for Album of the Year at the 2018 Grammy Awards and won two awards, including Best Alternative Music Album.

Beck's ninth album, Hyperspace (2019), was a return to his more introspective sound. It featured the singles "Uneventful Days," "Saw Lightning," and "Dark Places," all of which charted on the Billboard Hot 100. The album was nominated for Album of the Year at the 2020 Grammy Awards and won two awards, including Best Alternative Music Album.

Beck's music has consistently defied genre boundaries and has been praised for its creativity and diversity. He has been nominated for twelve Grammy Awards and has won four, including Album of the Year for Morning Phase (2014). He has also been honored with numerous awards throughout his career, including the prestigious Polar Music Prize (2013). His influence on the music industry has been immense, and he is widely considered to be one of the most innovative and influential artists of the past two decades.